---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="NYC Mouse Violations: DOHMH Code 04L | Cloakd"
  description="DOHMH code 04L is a mouse violation. It carries the same critical point weight as a rat violation. What inspectors look for, what the fine structure is, and what actually closes the vulnerability."
  path="/solutions/mouse-violations"
>

  <script type="application/ld+json">{
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is DOHMH violation code 04L?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "DOHMH code 04L is a mouse violation — evidence of mice in a food service establishment. It's a critical violation carrying a minimum of 5 points, the same weight as the rat violation code 04K. Combined with other violations, 04L can push a restaurant to a B or C grade on a single inspection." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What's the difference between a rat violation and a mouse violation in NYC?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "DOHMH code 04K covers rats; code 04L covers mice. Both are critical violations carrying a minimum of 5 points each. Both trigger re-inspection cycles. The active signs inspectors look for differ — rats leave larger droppings, grease marks, and gnaw damage, while mice leave smaller droppings, nesting material, and gnaw marks at lower heights — but the compliance exposure is identical." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Evolve work for mice as well as rats?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. SenesTech makes Evolve Mouse, a fertility management product using the same mechanism as Evolve Rat — gossypol-based soft bait that reduces reproductive output. The 90-day program structure applies identically: Phase 1 knockdown, Phase 2 Evolve Mouse deployment in managed bait stations, monthly track count monitoring." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can a restaurant have both a rat violation and a mouse violation at the same inspection?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Codes 04K and 04L are separate violations. A single inspection can cite both if the inspector finds evidence of rats and mice. That's a minimum of 10 critical points from rodent violations alone — before any other citations. At 28 points or more, a restaurant receives a C grade and is subject to closure." }
      }
    ]
  }</script>

  <!-- ─────────────────────────────────────── HERO ── -->
  <section class="pt-20 pb-24 px-6 max-w-6xl mx-auto">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-[#c96a3a] text-sm font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-6">
        Mouse violations — NYC
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-bold text-[#1c1814] leading-[1.08] tracking-tight mb-8">
        DOHMH code 04L is a mouse violation — and ignoring it while you manage the rats is how you end up with 10 critical points on one inspection.
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-[#1c1814]/70 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
        DOHMH violation code 04L covers evidence of mice. It's a critical
        violation carrying the same minimum point value as 04K, triggering
        the same re-inspection cycle, with an identical fine structure.
        Most operators don't find this out until an inspector does.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─────────────────────────────────────── THE CODE ── -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6 bg-[#f0ebe0]">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-[#c96a3a] text-sm font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-4">
        What the violation means
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-[#1c1814] leading-tight mb-6 max-w-2xl">
        04L: mice or evidence of mice in a food service establishment.
      </h2>

      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-start">
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">
            Code 04L is cited whenever an inspector finds evidence of mice
            anywhere in the food service establishment: prep areas, storage,
            front of house, or anywhere food is handled or stored. Evidence
            includes droppings, gnaw marks, nesting material, or live or
            dead rodents.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">
            At 5 critical points minimum, a single 04L citation combined with
            one other critical violation puts a restaurant above 9 points —
            triggering a B or C grade depending on total score. The 28-point
            threshold for a C grade and potential closure can be crossed with
            a handful of rodent and sanitation citations on a single visit.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">
            NYC restaurant closures for rodent violations are publicly
            reported. A mouse-related closure carries the same reputational
            damage as a rat closure — the distinction between 04K and 04L
            doesn't register with customers or local media.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          {[
            {
              label: 'Code 04L',
              body: 'Mice or evidence of mice — including live mice, dead mice, droppings, gnaw marks, or nesting material anywhere in the food service establishment.',
            },
            {
              label: 'Critical violation',
              body: 'Minimum 5 points per citation. Critical violations are weighted more heavily in scoring and trigger mandatory re-inspection cycles when uncorrected.',
            },
            {
              label: 'Fine structure',
              body: 'Fines range from $300 to $2,000 per violation depending on prior citation history and whether the violation is corrected at the time of inspection. Repeat violations carry higher penalties.',
            },
            {
              label: 'Re-inspection cycle',
              body: 'A critical violation triggers a follow-up inspection within a defined window. If the violation is still present at re-inspection, the point total is locked in and the grade reflects the full score.',
            },
          ].map(({ label, body }) => (
            <div class="border-l-2 border-[#c96a3a]/40 pl-4">
              <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-[#1c1814] mb-1">{label}</h3>
              <p class="text-base text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">{body}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─────────────────────────────────────── WHAT INSPECTORS LOOK FOR ── -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-[#c96a3a] text-sm font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-4">
        What inspectors look for
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-[#1c1814] leading-tight mb-12 max-w-2xl">
        Mouse evidence is harder to clear than most operators expect.
      </h2>

      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        {[
          {
            sign: 'Droppings',
            detail: 'Small rod-shaped droppings, typically 3–6mm, found along walls, behind equipment, in storage areas, and inside cabinets. A single mouse produces 50–75 droppings per day. NYC DOHMH health inspectors check corners, shelf edges, and floor gaps.',
          },
          {
            sign: 'Gnaw marks',
            detail: 'Mice gnaw continuously to keep their teeth in check. Look for gnaw marks on food packaging, wood baseboards, cardboard, and wiring. Marks are typically at lower heights than rat gnaw damage. Gnaw marks also indicate harborage points nearby.',
          },
          {
            sign: 'Nesting material',
            detail: 'Shredded paper, fabric, insulation, or soft material gathered in concealed areas — behind equipment, inside wall voids, in rarely moved storage. Nesting presence indicates established activity, not just transient rodents.',
          },
          {
            sign: 'Grease/rub marks',
            detail: 'Mice leave faint smear marks along regularly traveled paths — wall edges, pipe runs, and entry points. Less pronounced than rat grease marks but visible on close inspection.',
          },
          {
            sign: 'Live or dead mice',
            detail: 'Direct sighting of live or dead mice anywhere in the establishment. This is an automatic 04L citation regardless of other conditions.',
          },
          {
            sign: 'Entry points',
            detail: 'Gaps as small as 6mm (the diameter of a pencil) are sufficient entry for a mouse. Inspectors note unsealed pipe penetrations, gaps under doors, and cracks at wall junctions as contributing conditions.',
          },
        ].map(({ sign, detail }) => (
          <div class="bg-[#f0ebe0] rounded-xl p-5">
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-[#1c1814] mb-2">{sign}</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">{detail}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─────────────────────────────────────── RATS AND MICE TOGETHER ── -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6 bg-[#f0ebe0]">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-[#c96a3a] text-sm font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-4">
        When both are present
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-[#1c1814] leading-tight mb-6 max-w-2xl">
        04K and 04L can be cited at the same inspection.
      </h2>

      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-start">
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">
            Rats and mice rarely share territory — rats dominate and displace
            mice when both are present in the same space. But in a commercial
            building with multiple floors, compartments, or adjacent units,
            rats and mice can occupy separate areas simultaneously.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">
            A single DOHMH inspection at a NYC restaurant that cites both
            04K and 04L produces a minimum of 10 critical points from
            rodent violations alone.
            Combined with routine sanitation citations, crossing the 28-point
            closure threshold becomes straightforward.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">
            Most pest control programs address rats and mice as separate
            problems with separate treatments. The 90-day fertility management
            program addresses both simultaneously — Evolve Rat and Evolve
            Mouse deployed in the same two-phase structure.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-[#1c1814]/8 rounded-xl p-8">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-[#1c1814]/45 mb-6">Point math — combined rodent violations</p>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            {[
              { item: 'Code 04K — rats or evidence of rats', points: '5+ pts' },
              { item: 'Code 04L — mice or evidence of mice', points: '5+ pts' },
              { item: 'Subtotal — rodent violations alone', points: '10+ pts', highlight: true },
              { item: 'Typical sanitation violations (2–3)', points: '6–9 pts' },
              { item: 'Total — realistic inspection score', points: '16–19+ pts', highlight: true },
              { item: 'Grade B threshold', points: '14–27 pts' },
              { item: 'Grade C / potential closure', points: '28+ pts' },
            ].map(({ item, points, highlight }) => (
              <div class={`flex justify-between items-center py-2 ${highlight ? 'border-t border-b border-[#1c1814]/8' : ''}`}>
                <p class={`text-base ${highlight ? 'font-semibold text-[#1c1814]' : 'text-[#1c1814]/65'}`}>{item}</p>
                <p class={`text-base font-semibold flex-shrink-0 ml-4 ${highlight ? 'text-[#c96a3a]' : 'text-[#1c1814]/45'}`}>{points}</p>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─────────────────────────────────────── THE PROGRAM ── -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-[#c96a3a] text-sm font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase mb-4">
        How the program addresses it
      </p>
      <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-[#1c1814] leading-tight mb-12 max-w-2xl">
        Same two-phase structure. Separate fertility management for each species.
      </h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        {[
          {
            step: '1',
            label: 'Phase 1 knockdown — both species',
            body: 'Your existing pest control vendor treats for both rats and mice in Phase 1. Standard treatment methods work for both. The fertility layer goes in after a documented clean baseline is established for both.',
          },
          {
            step: '2',
            label: 'Evolve Mouse deployment',
            body: 'Evolve Mouse is a separate SenesTech product using the same gossypol-based mechanism as Evolve Rat. Stations are placed along mouse travel paths — typically at lower heights, along wall edges, and near food storage. Same monthly monitoring and replenishment schedule.',
          },
          {
            step: '3',
            label: 'Separate track count monitoring',
            body: 'Mouse tracking plates and rat tracking plates are deployed and tracked separately. Each has its own trend line in the monitoring record. This produces documentation specific to each violation code — useful if you\'re managing an active 04K and an active 04L simultaneously.',
          },
          {
            step: '4',
            label: '90-day monitoring record',
            body: 'The final report covers both species: track presence and density data by species, station-by-station breakdown, and a documented trend line you can hand to a DOHMH inspector as evidence of active management of both 04K and 04L conditions.',
          },
        ].map(({ step, label, body }) => (
          <div class="bg-[#f0ebe0] rounded-xl p-6">
            <div class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-[#c96a3a]/10 text-[#c96a3a] text-sm font-bold flex items-center justify-center mb-4">{step}</div>
            <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-[#1c1814] mb-3">{label}</h3>
            <p class="text-base text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed">{body}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─────────────────────────────────────── CTA ── -->
  <section class="py-24 px-6 bg-[#f0ebe0]">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
      <div class="max-w-2xl">
        <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-[#1c1814] leading-tight mb-6">
          Rats and mice. One program. One monitoring record.
        </h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-[#1c1814]/65 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          Tell us whether you're managing an active 04K, an active 04L,
          or both. We'll outline the station plan for your property and
          what the 90-day monitoring record will document.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
          <a
            href="/get-started"
            class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-7 py-4 text-base font-semibold rounded bg-[#b85530] text-[#faf8f4] hover:bg-[#c96a3a] transition-colors"
          >
            Start the 90-day program
          </a>
          <a
            href="/dohmh-rodent-violation-nyc"
            class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-7 py-4 text-base font-medium rounded border border-[#1c1814]/15 text-[#1c1814]/70 hover:text-[#1c1814] hover:border-[#1c1814]/25 transition-colors"
          >
            Rat violations (04K)
          </a>
          <a
            href="/what-to-expect"
            class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-7 py-4 text-base font-medium rounded border border-[#1c1814]/15 text-[#1c1814]/70 hover:text-[#1c1814] hover:border-[#1c1814]/25 transition-colors"
          >
            What to expect
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Base>
